She moved to a blank page and wrote the date on it. Below it, she wrote "11/05/648 - 13/12/648."
"Are you rereading memories?" Ivory asked, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? It's only a few days away."
Kari tapped twice on the lantern. No. Ivory had been right. The Ice King never let Kari out, because she was "a mistake" in his eyes. She was born mute, and she was the only girl in the family, which was otherwise composed only of boys.
Ivory was one too, in her own way. When she had revealed her non-binary identity, it was as if the world had changed too. She had been given tasks that condemned her to solitude, as punishment for her difference.
Iel also had to remain in service to the princess, but it wasn't too bad, because it gave her a friend.
"C'est bientôt ton anniversaire, je crois ?", demanda Ivory, se rappelant que l'anniversaire de la princesse tombait dans quelques jours. Kari hocha la tête, un éclat triste dans ses yeux bleu pâle.
"Tu veux le fêter ?" Tout en posant la question, iel se souvint de ce qu'elle lui avait répondu la dernière fois.
Non, botta Kari en touche. Ivory savait que c'était un sujet difficile pour elle. C'était le jour où elle avait été confinée dans sa chambre et que sa mère avait été bannie. Ivory était encore bébé quand c'était arrivé, mais iel se souvint de l'indignation des serviteurs et des habitants. Iel avait entendu dire que la reine Eirwen était une bonne reine, mais qu'elle avait aussi cette faculté étrange de prédire l'avenir.
"Bon... qu'as-tu envie de faire ?", demanda-t-iel. Kari leva les yeux avec enthousiasme. Elle tendit un papier à Ivory. Mais quand iel y jeta un œil...
Toile de peinture 15 cm x 15 cm
White, several shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
Easel
"Do you want me to find these things for you?" said Ivory, turning towards the silent princess who was frantically typing, shaking her braids back and forth. "Yes?" Iel giggled slightly at seeing the usually reserved princess getting excited about something. It was the first time she had asked for something unrelated to books and not found in her room.
"Okay. See you later?" offered Ivory, standing up and making her way through the pile of papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded and plunged back into her memories, wrapping herself again in her thick comforter.
She stepped out of the room with relief. The princess was finally stepping out of her comfort zone by asking for things that weren't within her domain, like painting.
She turned back through the corridors, trying not to listen to the whispers of the maids.
"I've heard she's possessed by Queen Eirwen, that's why she always goes into that room."
"I've heard she eats children in this room."
"She looks like a man, doesn't she?"
Iel covered their ears, because trying to ignore it wasn't working. Iel headed toward the royal painter's chamber, which was located in the east wing, second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as intricately carved as Kari's. It featured a white dragon, one of the six primordial dragons, who according to legend had created Frostfell. It was normal for the painter to display it on his door. He loved the story.
Iel opened the door, expecting to find a normal scene. Paint splatters everywhere, pencils and papers scattered around the room, easels covering every last centimeter of the wall. Surprisingly, Iel saw none of this. The room was tidy and there was a red velvet background with a stool just in front. On the stool sat Prince Aquilo, being painted.
"Ah, hello, Ivory! You're here to watch your future king pose for a portrait?" asked Aquilo to Ivory, giving her a wink.
"Pardon, petit prince", répondit-iel en l'ignorant partiellement, pour chercher les objets que sa silencieuse amie souhaitait. "Je suis là juste pour récupérer des fournitures".
"Ah, la fillette va repartir très vite ?", demanda Aquilo, "Mais je voulais te voir !"
"Eh bien, pas moi". Ivory avait trouvé les fournitures d'art de sa liste et les avait placées dans une caisse qu'iel avait dénichée. "Et je ne suis pas une fille."
Le prince n'y avait pas pensé toutefois. "Oh ma chérie, tu sais bien que c'est juste une phase ! Ça te passera quand tu auras grandi !", marmonna-t-il.
"Je dois y aller", dit-iel, soudain mal à l'aise, à cause des paroles du prince, qui lui rappelaient tout le mal que les gens disaient au sujet de son identité de genre. Je veux vraiment m'éloigner de lui.
"Tu are you leaving already?" The Prince appeared immediately at the door, ignoring the complaints of the royal painter.
"That is not the behavior of a future king!", he reprimanded him.
"No one will know. The others will not believe you, and the painter will say nothing if he wants to stay alive." He turned back to the painter for a second, then leaned toward Ivory. "What do you say to a date?" He shivered. Of course, he had received many threats in the past, but never from a prince, let alone an heir to the throne.
"Do you not know what the word no means?", he shouted, pushing the prince aside.
"Not at all," answered Aquilo with a smile. Obviously, the prince who gets everything he wants does not know what this word means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why would you want to go on a date with me instead of with others? You must have a hundred suitors, at least?"
He interrupted her, still smiling all the time: "Exactly 500." He pushed his hair back, making it fly in the cold air.
"So why me instead of someone else? I'm the threat to the palace." Iel wrapped her arms around her body.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Aquilo placed his finger under her chin and forced Ivory to look at him.
